NAME		istat  --  get inode status
.sp
.ti 0
SYNOPSIS	istat_____ inumber\d1\u ...
.sp
.ti 0
DESCRIPTION	istat_____
gives information about one or more i-nodes
on the given file system /dev/rk0________.
.sp
The information is basically in the same for
as that for stat(I),
All information is self-explanatory except the mode.
The mode is a seven-character string whose characters mean the
following:
.sp
.in +5
.ti -2
1 a: i-node is allocated
.br
u: i-node is free (no file)
.ti -2
2 s: file is small (smaller than 4096 bytes)
.br
l: file is large

.ti -2
3 d: file is a directory
.br
x: file is executable
.br
u: set user ID on execution
.br
-: none of the above
.ti -2

4 r: owner can read
.br
-: owner cannot read

.ti -2
5 w: owner can write
.br
-: owner cannot write

.ti -2
6 r: non-owner can read
.br
-: non-owner cannot read
.ti -2

7 w: non-owner can write
.br
-: non-owner cannot write
.in -5
.sp
The owner is almost always given in symbolic form;  however
if he cannot be found in "/etc/uids" a number is given.
.sp
If the number of arguments to stat____ is not exactly 1
a header is generated identifying the fields of the status information.
.sp
.ti 0
FILES		/etc/uids,
/dev/rk0
.sp
.ti 0
SEE ALSO	stat(I) ls(I) (-l option)
.sp
.ti 0
DIAGNOSTICS	"name?" for any error.
.sp
.ti 0
BUGS		istat_____
should take an optional alternate filesystem argument.
.sp
